Through my engagement with critical digital humanities, I'm increasingly interested in the study of data work and its influence on processes of knowledge production {% cite GengnagelLang2026 %}. 

After preliminary work on dataset documentation practices  {% cite Lang2025DocumentingDatasets %}, 
I have articulated dataset audit as a practical strategy for identifying and addressing data gaps {% cite ‎LangSuarezCronauer2026‎ %}.
This is closely connected to fields such as critical AI studies, which increasingly recognise data and data work as central sources of bias and unethical outcomes in computational systems. 

Recognizing the sheer amount of hidden labour and data work required for computational humanities research, I have examined what it means to _do_ computational history {% cite Lang2026DoingComputationalHistory %}.
I have also investigated invisibilised labour in Computational Humanities contexts through the lenses of data work and the invisible technician discourse {% cite Lang2027_TwoTierCH_Feminisms %}.
